00:00:49.220 --> 00:00:54.920
is the lead for the Product
Marketing Team for Search Advertising and

00:00:54.920 --> 00:00:58.040
a former student of Mike's is
going to come up and do that part of the introduction.

00:00:58.040 --> 00:01:10.380
Gopi Kallayil: Thanks, Evan.
In 2002, I had a momentary lapse of reason

00:01:10.380 --> 00:01:14.310
and signed up for a
experiential leadership program that took

00:01:14.310 --> 00:01:17.970
us all on an expedition to
Mount Everest base camp.

00:01:17.970 --> 00:01:22.430
Due to political trouble in Nepal that year,
the expedition leader

00:01:22.430 --> 00:01:27.670
decided to move the expedition to Mount Kanchenjunga
in the Himalayas.

00:01:27.670 --> 00:01:32.590
It's the third highest mountain in the world
and extremely demanding.

00:01:32.590 --> 00:01:36.420
The course was intended to be a experiential
leadership course, so the

00:01:36.420 --> 00:01:42.710
first day, the leader of the program asked
me to be leader for a day.

00:01:42.710 --> 00:01:47.420
And at that very first day, we were caught
in the midst of the worse

00:01:47.420 --> 00:01:56.580
Himalayan storm had ever seen.
These fierce winds -- that's experiential

00:01:56.580 --> 00:01:59.120
leadership with Matt Kolinsky
on the other end.

00:01:59.120 --> 00:02:03.259
So we were caught on this worst Himalayan
storm ever seen with crazy

00:02:03.259 --> 00:02:09.909
winds and sheets of ice everywhere.
One of the members of the group, Lynn Dan,

00:02:09.909 --> 00:02:14.709
told me that evening, as she
was sitting in this tent about to blown away

00:02:14.709 --> 00:02:19.489
that this was the first
ever night out in a tent --

00:02:19.489 --> 00:02:22.719
[laughter]
-- and how terrified she was.

00:02:22.719 --> 00:02:28.980
So these situations involve real -- in a difficult
life situations.

00:02:28.980 --> 00:02:33.189
Because during that one day, I had to make
decisions that took into

00:02:33.189 --> 00:02:36.799
account the safety and well-being of the other
members of the group,

00:02:36.799 --> 00:02:42.919
the Sherpas, and even the yaks that carried
our baggage up the

00:02:42.919 --> 00:02:48.189
mountains.
The leader of that expedition was Mike Useem.

00:02:48.189 --> 00:02:51.580
And this is how he teaches his student leadership
but not by using two

00:02:51.580 --> 00:02:55.540
by two metrics as -- but by actually putting
people in the midst of

00:02:55.540 --> 00:02:59.519
difficult life situations where you have to
call for your leadership

00:02:59.519 --> 00:03:04.540
that can effect the life and well-being of
other people.

00:03:04.540 --> 00:03:07.189
I've had the pleasure, privilege, and honor
of being Mike's student at

00:03:07.189 --> 00:03:10.870
the Wharton School of Business at the University
of Pennsylvania, where

00:03:10.870 --> 00:03:16.370
as Evan mentioned, he's also the Director
for Center for Leadership and

00:03:16.370 --> 00:03:18.299
Change.
And yes, Mike is a scholar.

00:03:18.299 --> 00:03:22.459
He's the author of more than five books, including
his latest, which

00:03:22.459 --> 00:03:26.879
he'll talk about today, "The Go Point: When
It's Time to Decide".

00:03:26.879 --> 00:03:32.779
But what was endeared Mike to me as a teacher
is the fact that he's a

00:03:32.779 --> 00:03:36.939
fantastic storyteller.
And the way he likes to teach leadership is

00:03:36.939 --> 00:03:40.760
either by putting his
students in certain situations or making them

00:03:40.760 --> 00:03:44.150
walk through the
leadership situations of other leaders who

00:03:44.150 --> 00:03:48.989
