00:07:01.639 --> 00:07:05.189
Smith.
I'd like you to see what he looked like.

00:07:05.189 --> 00:07:09.969
This will help us focus on what we're referencing
here.

00:07:09.969 --> 00:07:13.699
Gustavus Smith, upper left-hand corner.
I think everybody is just blanking.

00:07:13.699 --> 00:07:19.949
You've thought about Jeb Stewart and Ulysses
S. Grant and Robert E.

00:07:19.949 --> 00:07:24.280
Lee and George Mead, and Sheridan and Sherman,
but we're a little bit

00:07:24.280 --> 00:07:28.349
stuck on Smith even though he was one of the
Confederacy's great

00:07:28.349 --> 00:07:34.960
commanding officers.
And here's why he's totally forgettable: June

00:07:34.960 --> 00:07:43.229
1st, 1862 -- it's a
tough to see map up there -- the United States,

00:07:43.229 --> 00:07:49.039
in mortal conflict now
with the Confederacy which is created in 1861.

00:07:49.039 --> 00:07:54.210
South Carolina quits, 11 -- 10 other states
joined to form the CSofA

00:07:54.210 --> 00:07:59.180
the Confederate States of America, and in
the spring of 1862, the

00:07:59.180 --> 00:08:06.509
United States, the 22 remaining states, decide
 -- it decides to end the

00:08:06.509 --> 00:08:12.419
Civil War, 1862.
It, of course, won't end until 1865, but the

00:08:12.419 --> 00:08:16.330
U.S. decides to end the
war in 1862 or least it thought it could,

00:08:16.330 --> 00:08:23.259
Abraham Lincoln presiding
leader of the moment, by sending a force -- arrow

00:08:23.259 --> 00:08:27.349
on the right-hand
side of that photograph or that map rather

00:08:27.349 --> 00:08:32.130
there -- from Washington
down to what is then called, still is called

00:08:32.130 --> 00:08:37.860
Fort Monroe not to far
from Norfolk, Virginia, and to march up then,

00:08:37.860 --> 00:08:42.229
still called the
Peninsula to attack Richmond, the capital

00:08:42.229 --> 00:08:46.370
of the Confederacy.
The premise, a little bit false, but accepted

00:08:46.370 --> 00:08:50.760
at the time is that if
you could capture Jefferson Davis, President

00:08:50.760 --> 00:08:55.130
of the breakaway
Confederate States of America and take over

00:08:55.130 --> 00:08:59.570
his White House in
Richmond, Virginia, maybe capture a good bit

00:08:59.570 --> 00:09:02.529
of the defending forces,
that could end the Civil War.

00:09:02.529 --> 00:09:08.560
That's the plan.
So 125,000 U.S. soldiers are landed are Fort

00:09:08.560 --> 00:09:13.880
Monroe -- lower right-hand
corner in that map -- and they begin to march

00:09:13.880 --> 00:09:16.589
in a northwestern
direction towards Richmond.

00:09:16.589 --> 00:09:21.240
A little hard to see but it's in the upper
left-hand corner there.

00:09:21.240 --> 00:09:25.959
If you're Jefferson Davis, you're concerned
about the army that's

00:09:25.959 --> 00:09:32.690
defending the capital.
It's about 65,000 strong only, led by commanding

00:09:32.690 --> 00:09:37.269
officer Joseph
Johnston, outnumbered 2 to 1.

00:09:37.269 --> 00:09:41.740
Of course, you got home court advantage, Johnston
is defending

00:09:41.740 --> 00:09:47.230
Richmond, home -- home field.
Still, 2 to 1.

00:09:47.230 --> 00:09:51.060
It does not look maybe all that promising
for Jefferson Davis because

00:09:51.060 --> 00:09:54.940
he knows if he's captured, he'll probably
be hung.

00:09:54.940 --> 00:09:57.650
So there's a little bit of a personal concern
here not to mention his

00:09:57.650 --> 00:10:01.910
concern about the future of the country that
leads him -- in an era

00:10:01.910 --> 00:10:07.870
without any Nexus One telephones or even a
Blackberry, to go out to see

00:10:07.870 --> 00:10:11.730
what's going on in the frontline.
It's hard to believe there was such an era,

00:10:11.730 --> 00:10:19.260
but in 1862, May 31st, 1862
anyway, Joseph Johnston, the commanding officer

00:10:19.260 --> 00:10:24.399
of the Confederate
force that is preventing the fall of Richmond,

00:10:24.399 --> 00:10:28.070
the frontline of Joe
Johnston's defensive line around Richmond

00:10:28.070 --> 00:10:33.630
is only about five miles from
the center of town -- Jefferson Davis, President,

00:10:33.630 --> 00:10:38.639
rides out, this as if
Barack Obama decides to pick up and go to

00:10:38.639 --> 00:10:42.960
Kandahar, Afghanistan, to see
what's going directly in the field.

00:10:42.960 --> 00:10:47.449
That's exactly what Joe Johnston now has at
his back as his boss

00:10:47.449 --> 00:10:53.800
Jeff Davis goes out to take a look.
Jefferson Davis, within a few feet of Joe

00:10:53.800 --> 00:11:01.110
Johnston, sees Joe hit by
shrapnel and hit by a bullet at the same time.

00:11:01.110 --> 00:11:08.089
This is May 31st, 1862, not fatal.
Jefferson Davis walks over and says something

00:11:08.089 --> 00:11:10.000
like this, "Joe, you're
not looking too good right now".

00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:15.880
And Joe says, "Well, sir, I've been -- maybe
mortally wounded, to tell

00:11:15.880 --> 00:11:19.790
you the truth".
It's not but it's a very serious injury, and

00:11:19.790 --> 00:11:24.210
so Joe Johnston is asked
by Jeff Davis -- Jefferson Davis, to show

00:11:24.210 --> 00:11:29.990
the right respect here, is
asked who his replacement is that hopefully

00:11:29.990 --> 00:11:33.889
will defend Richmond
against its eminent overrun by the United

00:11:33.889 --> 00:11:40.360
States of America.
He says my number two guy, Gustavus W. Smith

00:11:40.360 --> 00:11:46.070
is my able replacement.
Gustavus W. Smith, a career which actually

00:11:46.070 --> 00:11:50.670
looks very good.
A bearing which is professional, sounded and

00:11:50.670 --> 00:11:55.600
looked like, has a CV that
is very leadership-like as well.

00:11:55.600 --> 00:11:59.759
Looks like a leader, acts like a leader, the
resume says it all, West

00:11:59.759 --> 00:12:04.600
Point has risen up to the number two person
in the army that's

00:12:04.600 --> 00:12:08.800
defending Richmond against it's eminent overrunning
by the United

00:12:08.800 --> 00:12:16.209
States, he -- on the spot, this is a literal
statement now, gets a

00:12:16.209 --> 00:12:22.050
battlefield promotion.
So Gustavus Smith, his boss down, Jeff Davis

00:12:22.050 --> 00:12:26.089
walks over and says, "Gus,
you're it.

00:12:26.089 --> 00:12:30.800
I hereby appoint you commanding officer of
the Army of Northern

00:12:30.800 --> 00:12:38.529
Virginia and you're going to prevent my hanging.
I hope you got some ideas now to do that".

00:12:38.529 --> 00:12:42.610
Gustavus Smith, this hand, gives a salute.
"Thank you for the battlefield promotion.

00:12:42.610 --> 00:12:46.290
I've always wanted to be a commanding officer.
I'm going to write home about this my kids

00:12:46.290 --> 00:12:50.060
are going to show me some
respect now".

00:12:50.060 --> 00:12:56.339
At that point, Jefferson Davis says to Gustavus
W. Smith, "Gus, now that

00:12:56.339 --> 00:13:02.430
you're in charge of saving the Confederacy,
what's your plan"?

00:13:02.430 --> 00:13:05.090
And Gustavus Smith, keep in mind, he is number
two, this is as if Joe

00:13:05.090 --> 00:13:08.779
Biden suddenly becomes President, he's probably
had to think about what

00:13:08.779 --> 00:13:13.540
he's might to do, Gustavus Smith says, "Give
me a few minutes to think

00:13:13.540 --> 00:13:20.940
about that, sir".
That's a little bit of a setback to his president.

00:13:20.940 --> 00:13:26.069
Jefferson Davis wanders off, returns 24 hours
later, and says, "Joe --

00:13:26.069 --> 00:13:29.980
Gus, rather.
Gus, you've had time now to give some thought

00:13:29.980 --> 00:13:33.009
to your strategic plan,
what is it"?

00:13:33.009 --> 00:13:40.701
And Gustavus W. Smith famously, or infamously,
says, "Sir, to tell you

00:13:40.701 --> 00:13:47.269
the truth, I've got no plan.
Do you have any good ideas"?

00:13:47.269 --> 00:13:54.290
Now, Jeff Davis had many well-known flaws,
one of which, though -- it

00:13:54.290 --> 00:13:59.379
was not -- was he was able to make good and
timely decisions.

00:13:59.379 --> 00:14:07.500
He said on the spot, "Gus, I hate to tell
you, but you are history".

00:14:07.500 --> 00:14:11.500
Actually, the opposite.
But we use that phrase, you're history, you're

00:14:11.500 --> 00:14:15.899
fired.
And Gustavus W. Smith becomes, in a sense,

00:14:15.899 --> 00:14:19.879
part of our non-history,
completely forgotten.

00:14:19.879 --> 00:14:25.170
But he is fired 24 hours later because Jefferson
Davis had a great

00:14:25.170 --> 00:14:31.449
leader, a commanding officer of a huge army,
65,000 strong that when

00:14:31.449 --> 00:14:36.230
all was said and given command, put in a leadership
position, could not

00:14:36.230 --> 00:14:40.860
take command.
Unable to make a decision, unable to conjure

00:14:40.860 --> 00:14:44.660
up a plan within which to
make decisions.

00:14:44.660 --> 00:14:50.790
At this point, to finish off this account,
Jefferson Davis says to his

00:14:50.790 --> 00:14:57.600
military aide standing right over here named
Robert E. Lee, Davis says

00:14:57.600 --> 00:15:02.639
"Bob, are you busy right now"?
And Lee says, "Of course not, sir, whatever

00:15:02.639 --> 00:15:09.800
you would like".
Robert E. Lee a long career in the Armed Services.

00:15:09.800 --> 00:15:13.050
When the war begins he is still a colonel
which is a below a General

00:15:13.050 --> 00:15:18.069
Officer, but now he's the military aide to
Jefferson Davis.

00:15:18.069 --> 00:15:25.709
And on June 1st, 1862, here's the phrase -- Robert
E. Lee comes to

00:15:25.709 --> 00:15:31.210
command, it's a phrase.
Jeff Davis says to Lee, "With Gustavus Smith

00:15:31.210 --> 00:15:34.709
gone, I'd like you to
become the commanding officer of the Army

00:15:34.709 --> 00:15:40.170
of Northern Virginia".
Lee takes command, didn't look a whole lot

00:15:40.170 --> 00:15:45.319
different from Gustavus
Smith by way of resume, by way of deportment,

00:15:45.319 --> 00:15:50.490
demeanor, you name it.
But the difference was Lee could make decisions

00:15:50.490 --> 00:15:55.980
timely, never perfect,
but usually pretty good and Smith could not.

00:15:55.980 --> 00:16:01.259
Hence, in the United States now there are
about 60 Robert E. Lee

00:16:01.259 --> 00:16:05.680
elementary schools.
There are no Gustavus W. Smith elementary

00:16:05.680 --> 00:16:10.189
schools.
And arguably one difference, among several,

00:16:10.189 --> 00:16:14.610
is that Robert E Lee was
pretty good at the art of making good and

00:16:14.610 --> 00:16:19.600
timely decisions.
Just to finish this off to make the point,

00:16:19.600 --> 00:16:25.279
Lee takes command June 1st,
the forward observers for the Union Army called

00:16:25.279 --> 00:16:31.560
the Army of the Potomac
can see the spires of downtown Richmond but

00:16:31.560 --> 00:16:33.509
that's as close as they're
ever going to get.

00:16:33.509 --> 00:16:39.779
Lee takes command makes a series of somewhat
 -- sometimes flawed, but

00:16:39.779 --> 00:16:45.060
usually very timely decisions and ultimately
pushes an army twice its

00:16:45.060 --> 00:16:51.860
size away from Richmond, off the Peninsula.
And by the way, the Union Army -- it's a name

00:16:51.860 --> 00:16:57.180
some of you will recall
-- the Union Army is commanded by a 34-year

00:16:57.180 --> 00:17:02.980
old named George McClellan.
And McClellan, with twice the force that Lee

00:17:02.980 --> 00:17:08.130
has, is defeated by Lee on
the Peninsula, Abraham Lincoln fires McClellan

00:17:08.130 --> 00:17:10.080
for the first of two
times.

00:17:10.080 --> 00:17:14.270
McClellan, a little bit also known for the
analysis paralysis.

00:17:14.270 --> 00:17:19.520
One end of the pole.
He was a commanding officer, fantastic.

00:17:19.520 --> 00:17:23.400
Soldiers loved him.
And they loved him in part because he would

00:17:23.400 --> 00:17:28.030
wait until everything was
perfect before he would do anything with the

00:17:28.030 --> 00:17:32.160
Army.
He had a case of analysis paralysis.

00:17:32.160 --> 00:17:36.330
It was often said during that era, George
McClellan would like every

00:17:36.330 --> 00:17:40.420
solider who ever worked for him to retire
as a veteran never having

00:17:40.420 --> 00:17:43.880
fired a shot.
Because everything was not perfect ever for

