00:34:05.910 --> 00:34:11.259
of Sciences?
And he says, I got a pretty good intuition

00:34:11.259 --> 00:34:15.710
because every Friday, I sit
down with whoever reports to me, we go over

00:34:15.710 --> 00:34:17.450
every decision during the
week.

00:34:17.450 --> 00:34:21.970
What was good, what was flawed, how can we
do better next week.

00:34:21.970 --> 00:34:28.190
No formal training, no MBA, no nothing.
But self-training created an intuition which

00:34:28.190 --> 00:34:31.039
has been pretty good.
Final exam, here we go.

00:34:31.039 --> 00:34:39.519
Take all that we've said, I'm going to take
us to a fateful day.

00:34:39.519 --> 00:34:41.039
1865 -- I'm going to skip over a bunch of
things here.

00:34:41.039 --> 00:34:43.350
It's going to make you a little bit dizzy.
Pardon me on this.

00:34:43.350 --> 00:34:52.210
Oh, wow, we're getting dizzy here.
Fateful day.

00:34:52.210 --> 00:34:58.280
This is April 9th, 1865, Robert E. Lee survives,
wins on the Peninsula

00:34:58.280 --> 00:35:05.710
back in 1862, never gives up command.
Lincoln was replacing generals every few months.

00:35:05.710 --> 00:35:09.759
Once Lee takes command, and remember the date,
June 1st, 1862, he never

00:35:09.759 --> 00:35:13.339
gives up command because he was as good as
they come.

00:35:13.339 --> 00:35:16.890
But he's defeated finally near Appomattox,
Virginia.

00:35:16.890 --> 00:35:22.049
April 9th, 1865, Lee surrenders.
Many paintings, no photographs.

00:35:22.049 --> 00:35:26.599
I've got one shown here.
He surrenders to Ulysses S. Grant.

00:35:26.599 --> 00:35:30.460
Grant, in his wisdom, sends a telegram to
President Lincoln, I have the

00:35:30.460 --> 00:35:35.240
privilege of announcing to you that the South's
biggest army, led by

00:35:35.240 --> 00:35:41.740
one Robert E. Lee, has unconditionally surrendered
today, Appomattox

00:35:41.740 --> 00:35:48.859
Courthouse, Virginia.
What's Lincoln's next thought?

00:35:48.859 --> 00:35:54.299
Put yourself in the mind of the man now in
the White House when you

00:35:54.299 --> 00:35:59.059
hear -- when you read that telegram comes
over from the War Department,

00:35:59.059 --> 00:36:02.250
what's your first thought?
What should be your first thought as the leader

00:36:02.250 --> 00:36:03.250
of the country?

00:36:03.250 --> 00:36:04.250
&gt;&gt; Hooray!

00:36:04.250 --> 00:36:05.250
[laughter]

00:36:05.250 --> 00:36:12.359
MIKE USEEM: Celebrate the end of four years
of absolute human carnage

00:36:12.359 --> 00:36:20.869
and the fact that the Union now has been restored.
And to focus on that, having fought -- this

00:36:20.869 --> 00:36:26.259
was almost total war for
its era: Think Atlanta, think Sherman's Campaign.

00:36:26.259 --> 00:36:31.740
We now have to reconcile.
That's up in Washington back to Appomattox,

00:36:31.740 --> 00:36:39.980
Virginia, in an odd move
Ulysses S. Grant picks a non-career officer

00:36:39.980 --> 00:36:43.579
who had taken leave from
Bowden College where he was teaching English

00:36:43.579 --> 00:36:47.720
and Speech, a guy named
Joshua Lawrence Chamberlain, anybody from

00:36:47.720 --> 00:36:54.740
Maine will know that name.
And he says, Grant to Chamberlain, a midlevel

00:36:54.740 --> 00:37:02.799
officer temporary, he
says, Chamberlain, on April 12th, I'm going

00:37:02.799 --> 00:37:08.519
to give you the historic
distinction of the formal surrender of the

00:37:08.519 --> 00:37:12.620
army of Robert E. Lee.
I order you to do the following: You're going

00:37:12.620 --> 00:37:19.140
to stand at the edge of
a field, 4,000 men in blue and a few women

00:37:19.140 --> 00:37:21.200
are going to be at attention
behind you.

00:37:21.200 --> 00:37:26.260
This is ceremonial now, three days later after
the signing, and all the

00:37:26.260 --> 00:37:30.470
Confederate units, a day of ignominy, have
to come up to where you're

00:37:30.470 --> 00:37:35.029
standing, they have to give you their flag,
what's called the colors

00:37:35.029 --> 00:37:40.490
for their unit and their weapons.
You have to take them.

00:37:40.490 --> 00:37:44.370
Everything else is up to you.
So here's the final exam.

00:37:44.370 --> 00:37:47.770
Got to think of -- we're almost out of time,
got to think about this

00:37:47.770 --> 00:37:51.670
quickly, you're Chamberlain, you've been given
the intent.

00:37:51.670 --> 00:37:56.309
Go back to that Marine Corps formulation but
all the decisions now

00:37:56.309 --> 00:38:03.200
within that intent are up to you.
So how would you script the formal surrender

00:38:03.200 --> 00:38:08.029
of Robert E. Lee's army?
What would you do?

00:38:08.029 --> 00:38:10.190
Somebody give us a quick voicing.
I'll put it on the air here.

00:38:10.190 --> 00:38:17.869
Well, it depends on what you want to achieve.
What's the point of the surrender?

00:38:17.869 --> 00:38:18.869
Yes?

00:38:18.869 --> 00:38:19.869
[off microphone]: Welcome home.

00:38:19.869 --> 00:38:21.710
MIKE USEEM: The statement here is welcome
home.

00:38:21.710 --> 00:38:24.849
And that is almost a perfect way to sum it
up.

00:38:24.849 --> 00:38:29.151
We hereby defeat you but the objective of
this war was not to do that

00:38:29.151 --> 00:38:35.839
but was to bring you back home.
So today is a day is a moment of reconciliation.

00:38:35.839 --> 00:38:39.839
Now we've got to take that and bring that
down tactically.

00:38:39.839 --> 00:38:43.609
So we're going to make a decision to reconcile
not humiliate.

00:38:43.609 --> 00:38:47.299
We've got to bring that down tactically.
And let me just reference how that is done

00:38:47.299 --> 00:38:52.190
with the following final
image, and we're now through the final exam

00:38:52.190 --> 00:38:57.660
successfully completed.
These are the 4,000 soldiers lined up here.

00:38:57.660 --> 00:39:03.460
This is Chamberlain, the temporary officer
from Maine, hard to see but

00:39:03.460 --> 00:39:10.849
in the lower left-hand, almost speck place
of this image is the first

00:39:10.849 --> 00:39:16.500
Confederate unit that's coming up a day of
ignominy, as far as they're

00:39:16.500 --> 00:39:20.730
concerned.
Chamberlain, without permission, but that

00:39:20.730 --> 00:39:26.359
was Lee's -- that was Grant's
purpose -- get the intent, you make the decisions,

00:39:26.359 --> 00:39:31.559
tells a subordinate
"Carry Arms."

00:39:31.559 --> 00:39:36.890
Many of us know the term "Present Arms."
It's a formal military posture, carry arms

00:39:36.890 --> 00:39:42.250
one notch below that in
parade formation, but only given when you

00:39:42.250 --> 00:39:47.339
want to show respect.
Great respect, normally only given to a Union

00:39:47.339 --> 00:39:51.509
Officer, a General who's
come on to the scene.

00:39:51.509 --> 00:39:54.480
Chamberlain tells his number two guy "carry
arms."

00:39:54.480 --> 00:40:00.349
The word goes down, the 4,000 people so displayed
suddenly move,

00:40:00.349 --> 00:40:05.569
musket comes over here, left hand across the
stock, the Confederate

00:40:05.569 --> 00:40:09.880
Officer coming down that muddy lane, same
tradition.

00:40:09.880 --> 00:40:14.299
They all come out of West Point more or less,
says to himself, whoa,

00:40:14.299 --> 00:40:19.809
carry arms.
I guess that's -- that's for us.

00:40:19.809 --> 00:40:23.210
So he in turn, still a little bit of authority
left.

00:40:23.210 --> 00:40:27.452
They're about to be disbanded.
He turns to his own subordinate number two

00:40:27.452 --> 00:40:30.589
officer and says "carry
arms."

00:40:30.589 --> 00:40:34.569
In the history of the Civil War, this becomes
known as the salute

00:40:34.569 --> 00:40:40.259
returning the salute.
And in the years after the end of the war,

00:40:40.259 --> 00:40:45.160
you mention the name Sherman
anywhere in Georgia and people are going to

00:40:45.160 --> 00:40:46.880
get red in the face all
over again.

00:40:46.880 --> 00:40:51.589
Some of you I know are from the South.
If you mention the name Chamberlain, those

00:40:51.589 --> 00:40:56.019
who knew about this incident
would say, Chamberlain, he was one of those

00:40:56.019 --> 00:40:58.829
people that displayed us
with respect.

00:40:58.829 --> 00:41:05.319
Let's see what does Lincoln want?
He wants to bring them back in.

00:41:05.319 --> 00:41:09.980
That's the intent.
No evidence that Chamberlain ever met Abraham

00:41:09.980 --> 00:41:15.749
Lincoln, but with that
intent known, reconciliation is required,

00:41:15.749 --> 00:41:22.440
a decision is made April 12th
by Chamberlain for respect to be displayed

00:41:22.440 --> 00:41:26.940
towards the defeated
Confederate Army.

00:41:26.940 --> 00:41:30.809
Maybe that's the way -- one way to sum this
up, decision making.

00:41:30.809 --> 00:41:36.220
Think the Marine Corps four-point formulation,
think Kathy Eisenhardt's

00:41:36.220 --> 00:41:41.600
five part formulation, think the four people
who nicely reported what

00:41:41.600 --> 00:41:45.680
they put into their decisions, read books
like Malcolm Gladwell on

00:41:45.680 --> 00:41:50.700
that, and maybe to all that how about this
as a final parting shot,

00:41:50.700 --> 00:41:55.930
don't you want people working for you when
they make good and timely

00:41:55.930 --> 00:42:01.450
decisions ultimately to think like a president,
to think like you own

00:42:01.450 --> 00:42:04.819
the company, to think that everything hangs
on you?

00:42:04.819 --> 00:42:08.200
And I think that with a guideline, hopefully
people working for you in

00:42:08.200 --> 00:42:12.730
their own leadership, will give you what you
want and what the company

00:42:12.730 --> 00:42:14.349
needs.
My pleasure, may you all decide.

00:42:14.349 --> 00:42:15.349
Thank you very much.

00:42:15.349 --> 00:42:15.350
[applause]

